    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>12 July 1849</date></p>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
          <p rend="indent(8)"><placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; <del><date>January</date></del> <date>July 12&#44; 1849</date></p>
			<p>To the honorable and famous sage&#44; <addressee>Rabbi Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I again want to call your attention to the price of your<lb/> prayer books and ask whether you would consider lowering it&#44;<lb/> in view of the fact that <persName>Frank&#39;s</persName> will cost only &#36;1.00&#44; and thus<lb/> make sales impossible. I do not&#44; however&#44; desire to give you<lb/> any advice. Do whatever you like. It might be preferable to<lb/> leave it at the old price&#44; since people will see how much handso&#45;<lb/>mer and more complete your prayer books are&#44; and will not<lb/> mind the higher price</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">The chief reason for my letter of today is the handsome<lb/> Torah about which I forgot in my last letter. It is a beautiful<lb/> specimen&#44; and I know that in your hands it is worth &#36;180<lb/> The trouble is that I haven&#39;t the acquaintanceship&#44; nor<lb/> the necessary connections&#44; and I prefer to give it to you &#36;20<lb/> cheaper than I could possibly get from congregations in<lb/> the course of a few months. I want to offer it to you for<lb/> only &#36;130. Let it be viewed by an impartial person and you will see<lb/> what a tremendous difference there is between such a torah<lb/> and the kind sold by <persName>Ottinger</persName>. I also have some woolen and<lb/> silk &#8220;talithim<add>&#63;</add>&#8221;&#44; some of which even the <persName>Rev. Isaacs</persName> bought<lb/> although he usually imports his directly.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Through your correspondence and acquaintanceship through<lb/>out the <placeName>United States</placeName> even with such Christian scholars as interest<lb/> themselves in Jewish knowledge&#44; or the study of Hebrew literature<lb/> you could do more than anyone else for my book business.<lb/> I do not say that you should dispose&#44; for me&#44; of calendars&#44;<lb/> &#8220;Aggadahs&#8221;&#44; and children&#39;s prayer books. Such things<lb/> I would certainly not suggest to you. But my catalogue<lb/> contains works&#44; the dissemination of which will certainly not reflect<lb/> upon you&#44; even though you are not their publisher. Finally&#44;<lb/> I require no cash from you for such books. I should only take<lb/> something as an exchange account from your publications. I<lb/> shall give you these things to be sold during a period of four or<lb/> five months.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I have already printed the catalogue and cannot expend<lb/> such a sum again. Had we discussed this matter previously&#44;</p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><date>7&#45;12&#45;1849</date></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
          <p>I should gladly have had this catalogue printed in<lb/> accordance with such an arrangement&#44; or through<lb/> <del>your</del> you. In view of the fact that the format of the catalogue<lb/> is the same as that of the Occident&#44; at least in the matter<lb/> of the size of the paper&#44; it can&#44; without harm&#44; be attached to<lb/> the next issue of the &#8220;Occident&#8221; without increasing<lb/> the postage cost&#44; or any other expense. On the cover one<lb/> might say that these books are obtainable through me or<lb/> through you. I hope you will agree to this.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">If you&#44; yourself&#44; don&#39;t want to buy the Torah<lb/> or do not know of any customer and if you consider it<lb/> worthwhile&#44; please insert&#44; in my name&#44; a small advertise&#45;<lb/>ment about it on the cover of the &#8220;Occident&#8221;. The Torah is<lb/> 28 inches long without the &#8220;etz chaim&#8221;&#42; The parchment and<lb/> the script are unusually handsome and fine. Pardon me<lb/> for burdening you again with my poor writing.</p>
          <p rend="indent(8)">most respectfully&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">Isidor Bush</persName></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><date>7&#45;12&#45;1849</date></p>
			<p>&#42;rollers</p>
          
        </body>
    </text>
